{"id":"physics/0109060","submitter":"Fran De Aquino","authors":"Fran De Aquino (Maranhao State University, Brazil)","title":"A Possibility of Gravity Control in Luminescent Materials","comments":"8 pages, PDF","journal-ref":"Published in Journal of New Energy, (October 2001), Vol. 6, Number\n  2, pp. 46-58","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  It was demonstrated (gr-qc/9910036) that the gravitational and inertial\nmasses are correlated by an adimensional factor, which depends on the incident\n(or emitted)radiation upon the particle. There is a direct correlation between\nthe radiation absorbed(or radiated) by the particle and its gravitational mass,\nindependently of the inertial mass. Only in the absence of electromagnetic\nradiation the mentioned factor becomes equal to one. On the other hand, in\nspecific electromagnetic conditions, it can be reduced, nullified or made\nnegative. This means that there is the possibility of the gravitational masses\ncan be reduced, nullified or made negative by means of electromagnetic\nradiation. This unexpected theoretical result was confirmed by an experiment\nusing Extra-Low Frequency(ELF) radiation on ferromagnetic material\n(gr-qc/0005107). Recently another experiment using UV light on phosphorescent\nplastic have confirmed the phenomenon. We present a complete explanation for\nthe alterations of the gravitational field in luminescent materials. This work\nindicates that the alterations of the gravitational field can be sufficiently\nstrong to invert the gravity on luminescent materials.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 24 Sep 2001 18:07:25 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 2 Oct 2001 00:05:05 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 8 Oct 2001 19:42:35 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Thu, 25 Oct 2001 16:18:51 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Mon, 7 Apr 2003 17:37:04 GMT"}],"update_date":"2010-06-11"}
